Heater profile technical documentation

Installation

I have saved the project to GitHub, the following will instruct you how to download and set up the code.

HPC

I would recommend setting up this project remotely on the HPC, as it is much quicker to load the house keeping data from RDS.

To get into the HPC type this into your terminal

ssh <your username>@login.hpc.ic.ac.uk

You can also SSH into the HPC from within VSCode. This is a bit too in depth to include here, just follow this tutorial.

We use Anaconda to manage Python and its packages. Follow the HPC wiki for how to install conda. If you are loading for the first time then type this in to the terminal

anaconda-setup

You then need to type this every time you log into a node on the HPC

module load anaconda3/personal

However, this gets very boring to do, so instead I run these commands so that this is done automatically

echo ". /rds/general/user/<your username>/home/anaconda3/etc/profile.d/conda.sh" >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc

Environment

We use conda to create separate environments. An environment is a way to separate out different instances of Python. This is useful as not all versions of packages are compatible with each other, therefore we rely on conda to work this out for us.

To install the packages, run this command in the terminal (if it says there is no env.yml, make sure you are in the right folder)

conda env create -f env.yml

We will mainly be using the following packages:

  • pandas for storing and manipulating the data in DataFrames
  • scikit-learn for the machine learning
  • matplotlib for plotting figures
  • cdflib to open .cdf files if needed

You should now have a folder called \home\anaconda3\envs\heaters

To enter the environment type 

conda activate heaters

if it says conda doesn't exist then try 

source activate heaters

after you do the module load line from above

Your terminal should now look a bit like this

Info

To double check, type python --version and you should see Python 3.9.15 (or at least 3.9)

Extra packages

If you need another package then follow their instructions online, but it will either be

conda install <package name>

or

python -m pip install <package name>
Warning

If it is only available using pip then it is really important to use the python -m above, so that the package is only installed in the environment and not for the global python interpreter, i.e. we want it to work with our heaters environment, not some other Python you might have installed

Project code

To download the code, either download the .zip file like so:

or if you have git installed then use:

git clone git@github.com:rlaker/Heaters.git

(Download Git for windows if you don't have git already.)

Pointing to folders

Warning

The above only downloads the code, you have to then same folder structure

You should have these folders:

  • Experimental/ holds some files I was playing around with
  • HK Data/ stores the cached house keeping data (in .csv) and also the Jupyter notebooks that experiment with these files.
  • Models/ to store the trained models
  • Profiles/ stores the heater profiles per day in .h5 format. Ask Ed to make these for you
    • Input are the profiles we need to learn from
    • Ouput are the predicted profiles from the model
  • testing/ just stores some quick .py files to test a few functions

Now we need to make sure the code knows where these folders are. Create a file called settings.py in the same folder as helpers.py and make sure these values are correct to your system

LOCAL_HK_FOLDER = "/rds/general/user/<your username>/home/Heaters/HK data/"
HP_FOLDER = "/rds/general/user/<your username>/home/Heaters/Profiles/Input/"
EXPORT_FOLDER = "/rds/general/user/<your username>/home/Heaters/Profiles/Output/"

We also need to make sure the code knows where to get more house keeping data, so update this variable

RDS_FOLDER = "/rds/general/user/<your username>/projects/solarorbitermagnetometer/live/production/"

I would recommend using VSCode so that you can open and read Jupyter notebooks ( .ipynb files)

Exploring House keeping features

HK Data/

These Jupyter notebooks ( .ipynb files) are where you can experiment/look at individual files of the house keeping data. The making of the features.csv is done in the next section.

The structure is similar between these files. For example, take the th_mag.ipynb file, which extracts features from files of the same name.

  1. We first load the right days to look at
start = datetime(2020,6,22)
end = datetime(2022,12,31)
dates = h.get_dates(start, end)

# I need to load all the data like normal, then decide how I can summarise that per day
if start < datetime(2020,6,22):
    raise Exception("not sorted out what to do with these big files yet, choose a later start time")

th_mag = h.load_HK("solo_ANC_sc-thermal-mag", start, end)
th_mag_per_day = th_mag.resample("1D").mean()
  1. Then make some initial plots of the RAW data
%matplotlib ipympl
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2,1,sharex=True)

axs[0].scatter(th_mag.index, th_mag['ANP_2_1_6 MAG OBS'], color = 'blue', label = 'OBS T')
axs[0].scatter(th_mag.index, th_mag['ANP_2_1_9 MAG IBS'], color = 'red', label = 'IBS T')

# using r'' makes Python interpret the string as raw
axs[0].set_ylabel(r'Temp. ($^{\circ}$)')
axs[0].legend(loc= 'upper right')

axs[1].scatter(th_mag.index, th_mag["ANP_2_1_6 MAG OBS"] - th_mag["ANP_2_1_9 MAG IBS"], color = 'black', label = 'OBS - IBS')
axs[1].set_ylabel('OBS - IBS (K)')

fig.autofmt_xdate()

Warning

When plotting files in Jupyter notebooks you can specify what backend is used with %matplotlib <backend>
The best ones are:

  • %matplotlib ipympl makes an interactive figure within the notebook
  • %matplotlib qt5 makes an interactive window outside the notebook
  • %matplotlib inline for generating a .png (not interactive)
  1. Make the features so there is only 1 value per day.

usually starts with a simply down sample

th_mag_per_day = th_mag.resample("1D").mean()

you can replace the .mean() with any function, such as:

  • .std()
  • .median()
  • .apply(<custom function>)
  1. Plot the final features
  2. Put features into a pandas DataFrame, which is how we will make one big DataFrame in the next section

Making the features

features.py

This Python file will create one big .csv file with all the features we want to learn from.

Running

The features.py file is designed to be run from the command line (terminal). This way it can just run on the HPC, which is much faster since the data doesn't have to move from Slough to London.

flags:

  • -s is the start date. As explained in the overview document, the current beast result come from training only on heater 2 which is after `2021-11-09
  • -e is the end date, by default this is 2023-05-21 at the time of writing.
  • -p is to plot the data in Figures/
  • --history is how many days back the features should be replicated.

e.g. the standard run would be

python features.py -s 2021-11-09 -p --history 4
Warning

Update these default flags if it isn't loading all the data you want

lcl

The data should be sourced from RDS for the first time and then cached as .csv by the code. However, because the LCL data takes so long, I just manually run through lcl.ipynb to create a HK data/mag_lcl.csv file.

Adding new features

Info

When you are happy with the features extracted from one of the .ipynb files, you need to copy that into the features.py file.

For example, for th_mag it looks like this

###############################################################################
### th_mag ###################################################################
###############################################################################
print("TH MAG")
print('')

th_mag = h.load_HK("solo_ANC_sc-thermal-mag", start, end)
th_mag_per_day = th_mag.resample("1D").median(numeric_only=True)


features['OBS T'] = th_mag_per_day["ANP_2_1_6 MAG OBS"].values
features['IBS T'] = th_mag_per_day["ANP_2_1_9 MAG IBS"].values
features['OBS minus IBS T'] = th_mag_per_day["ANP_2_1_6 MAG OBS"].values - th_mag_per_day["ANP_2_1_9 MAG IBS"].values

# time since dropped
encoded_temp = np.where(th_mag_per_day["ANP_2_1_6 MAG OBS"].values > -70, 1,0)

time_since = [0]
time_it_was_high = [0]
cumulative = [0]

cu_val = 0
length_high_temp = 0
days_since_drop = 0

for i in np.arange(1, encoded_temp.shape[0]):
	previous = encoded_temp[i-1]
	now = encoded_temp[i]
	if now > previous:
		# jump in temp
		#this takes care of just up and down I think
		length_high_temp = 1
		cu_val += 1
	elif now < previous:
		# drop in temp
		days_since_drop = 0
	else:
		# then values must be the same
		if now > 0.5:
			# we are in a high temp bit
			length_high_temp += 1
			cu_val += 1
		else:
			days_since_drop += 1
			if cu_val > 0:
				cu_val -= 1

	time_since.append(days_since_drop)
	time_it_was_high.append(length_high_temp)
	cumulative.append(cu_val)

features['time_since_T_high'] = time_since
# I don't think I need this now, cumulative models it better
features['time_it_was_high'] = time_it_was_high
features['cumulative'] = cumulative

N = 20
for feature_name in ['OBS T', 'IBS T', 'OBS minus IBS T']:
	features = h.reduce_cardinality(features, feature_name, N)

A few things to notice:

  • we have already selected start and end at this point in the code
  • we have already got a features DataFrame, so we just need to add our new columns
  • we reduce the cardinality, which was explained in the overview document

Cardinality

Reduces the number of values a feature is allowed to take.

This is with done with the helpers.reduce_cardinality(features, feature_name, N, bins = None)

If you just want to evenly bin the data into N = 20 bins then use

helpers.reduce_cardinality(features, feature_name, 20)

However, sometimes it is better to have custom bins, e.g. when there is steady data with only a few large outliers. We don't want 100 bins in between the steady data and the outliers, so just make some custom bin edges and put them into the function like so

bins = np.arange(-5,5+0.5,0.5)
bins = np.concatenate((np.array([-100]), bins, np.array([100])))
features = h.reduce_cardinality(features, 'SCM T grad', N, bins = bins)

Training the model

The code for this lives in files starting with train_<model>.py, but they are submitted to the HPC with the .psb files

There are several arguments to the training, many of which are just left on the default value.

Arguments

  • -i or --inst for which instrument to train on, IBS or OBS
    • default is OBS
  • -p or --period sets the downsampling period for training
    • default is '-1'
    • 1 is another good value to use
    • -1 uses the custom time steps set out in helpers.get_var_time_bins(ds_duration)
  • -d or --duration sets the duration through the profiles to learn from (seconds)
    • this is good for experimenting with learning just the first 5 minutes (300 seconds)
    • default is 900 seconds or 15 minutes
  • -t or --tune sets how the tuning of the model is done. Options are:
    • untuned for just the standard model from sklearn
    • tuned for some user set hyperparameters
    • bayes for the BayesSearchCV method of tuning hyperparameters. This takes much longer to run, since it is trying out many different combinations
    • I use this parameter to experiment with the tuning, for production you would want to set your own values for the tuned method (look in the code for when it says args.tune == "tuned")
  • --split determines how the daily heater profiles are split into training and test data
    • days - in this method each day is treated as separate. Training and test will be randomly selected days, with all the profiles stacked together
    • profiles instead takes random samples from all the days. In this way, we can learn more about the profiles, but can lead to overfitting!
  • --cv stands for cross validation which is used to test the performance of the model. I started using this for a bit, but then focussed on something else. Therefore, this part of the code is unfinished, but the argument is still here if you want to write this part up.
  • -w or --weights sets the code to try and use weights as part of the training. We originally tried to weight the profiles by "time through profile", which meant that it would learn more about the first couple of minutes. However, this idea was dropped but this argument still exists.
    • Random Forest does not accept weights like LightGBM did, so this argument is also obsolete for that reason.
    • If the model allows it, you could weight each day's profile by how much you believe it. For example, if the solar wind variability is high, the averaging method will not work. Therefore, the weights could be equal to the variance of solar wind fluctuations in that day
  • -v or --val sets how the validation is done.
    • This is completely unseen data to test if the model is just memorising the data. Also used for early stopping when using the LightGBM model
    • Can take values of latest or random
    • latest takes the validation data as the last few months of data available at the time. For me, I just made this the 2023 data
    • random takes random days before splitting into training and test data. However, this validation doesn't work as well because the model can "see" data around the validation set. Therefore, I would stick to the default of using latest
  • --rfe turns on Recursive Feature Elimination which attempts to only keep the most important features to train the model on. It does this by training a model and removing the least important variables, then repeating
    • In the line below, I have set the RFE to find the top 20 features, removing 1 at a time.
if args.rfe:
	rfe = RFE(estimator = RandomForestRegressor(), n_features_to_select=20, step = 1, verbose=1)
  • --coord sets the coordinate system to train on
    • rtn is for RTN coordinates, which is what I would keep it on
    • sph is for spherical coordinates, these look a bit more crazy
Warning

I know that is a lot of arguments to worry about, but this has all come from experimenting with different variables. I would say the most important ones are:

  • split
  • validation (if using LightGBM)
  • rfe

Therefore, my standard run would be something like

python train_RF.py -d 900 -p -1 --split profiles --rfe

Submitting a job to HPC

TLDR: submit a job like this

qsub rf_untuned.pbs

Check on the status with

qstat

Longer explanation:

Once you have run features.py there should be a HK data/features.csv. You can now train a model to learn from these features.

The actual code to train lives in either:

  • train_RF.py for random forest
  • train_lightgbm.py for LightGBM

The training is done using batch jobs on the HPC, these files end in .psb and look a bit like this

#PBS -l walltime=00:30:00
#PBS -l select=1:ncpus=9:mem=2gb

module load anaconda3/personal
source activate heaters

cd $PBS_O_WORKDIR

python train_RF.py -d 900 -p -1 --split profiles --rfe

#PBS -l walltime=00:30:00
#PBS -l select=1:ncpus=9:mem=2gb

These lines tell the HPC what kind of computing power you want. These parameters determine which queue you are put in.

module load anaconda3/personal
source activate heaters

loads the right anaconda environment. This assumes that the environment has been installed into /home/anaconda3/envs/heaters

cd $PBS_O_WORKDIR

Makes sure the data is loaded and saved from the same place as the .psb file we ran

python train_RF.py -d 900 -p -1 --split profiles --rfe

This is the line that actually runs, you could just run this on your own computer and not the HPC

Output of a run

By training a model, you will have created several files that are saved in Models/<model acronym>:

  • OBS_untuned_-1_900.joblib is the actual model which was untuned, had a --period of -1 and a duration of 900
  • OBS_untuned_-1_900_scaler.joblib is a saved scaler to undo the scaling applied when training the data
  • OBS_untuned_-1_900_features.joblib is an array saying whether RFE selected that variable or not
    • The way I have set this up is to use RFE everytime
    • However, you will probably get to a point where you know what the top 20 are. At this stage, I would change the features.py file to reflect this and not apply RFE anymore
  • rf_untuned.pbs.o8068122 is the output file from HPC for the run 8068122
    • This contains everything that Python printed, which is useful for seeing how things went
    • I usually focus on the model score and validation score, for example:
      • Test Score: 0.9935476356311813
      • Val Score: 0.6110385091866618
    • As you can see, the model fits too well on the test data and did not generalise to the unseen validation set
  • rf_untuned.pbs.e8068122 is the error file from the HPC, which tells you how your code failed

Checking the model output

interpreting.iypnb shows the results of the trained model

Warning

This was originally written to load 3 separate models from the LightGBM method, which has now been adapted to load the single model from the Random Forest method.

You can compare the prediction (red) to the real data (black) in time, such as:

Predicting profiles

predict.py is the same code as in interpreting.ipynb but it saves a predicted heater profile for each day. Technically, the data is interpolated back onto the original heater profile timestamps, just to make it easier to incorporate into the cleaning pipeline.

TLDR

So if you wanted to just run a full train, predict cycle

python features.py -s 2021-11-09 

qsub rf_untuned.psb

python predict.py --rfe
